### Day-11 Controlled and Uncontrolled Components in React

 ğŸ‘‹ âš›ï¸ Controlled and Uncontrolled Components in React ğŸ”†

 The React state will always act as "the source of truth".


âš™ï¸ Controlled Components
    ğŸ‘‰ Controlled components are forms that are handled entirely by a React component and a hook called useState.
    ğŸ‘‰ useState is a hook that automatically refreshes the application whenever a change is made to its state variable (prop). 
    ğŸ‘‰ Form elements become controlled elements once the value is set to a prop.
    ğŸ‘‰ It will track every change done to the form (every input down to the letter)



âš™ï¸ Uncontrolled Components
    ğŸ‘‰ Uncontrolled components are controlled by the DOM instead of an individual component.
    ğŸ‘‰ Uncontrolled components use the useRef attribute. You can use useRef as a way to access values from the DOM.
    ğŸ‘‰ We first bring in the useRef hook then we use a ref attribute in our JSX to give the current value to our ref variable. 
    ğŸ‘‰ This gives us access to the submitted form information.


Code Example: 

```
// Controlled Components

import React, { useState } from "react";

function Form() {
    const [name, setName] = useState("");

    console.log(name);

    return (
        <form>
            <input type="text" value={name} onChange=
                {(e) => setName(e.target.value)} />
            <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </form>
    );
}

export default Form;
-------------------------------------------------------------
// Uncontrolled Component

import React, { useRef } from "react";

function Form() {

    const ref = useRef();

    const handleSubmit = (e) => {
        e.preventDefault();
        console.log(ref.current.value)
    };

    return (
        <form>
            <input type="text" ref={ref} />
            <button type="submit" onClick= 
               {handleSubmit}>Submit</button>
        </form>
    );
}

export default Form;
```
